  "cells": [
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "# **Distant Reading**\n",
        "This notebook covers the macro-analysis of a manually curated dataset of 100 poems about recurring \"internet-famous\" subjects like Laika, the Two-Headed Calf, and the Anglerfish.\n",
        "## **Corpus Distribution**\n",
        "The poems in this dataset were strategically harvested from 5 major social media and microblogging platforms to capture the viral life cycle of social-media poetry.\n",
        "![Screenshot 2026-03-12 at 2.53.09 PM.png](data:image/png;base64,)\n",
        "## **Methods**\n",
        "\n",
        "1.   **Sentiment Analysis** to determine the tone\n",
        "2.   **Topic Modeling** to find the theme\n",
        "3.   **Computational Scansion** to understand rhythm\n",
        "4.   A series of iterative tools to find few figurative devices found in an elegies:\n",
        "      \n",
        "      * **Apostrophe**: Rule-based detection (second-person pronouns)\n",
        "      * **Refrain**: Line repetition detection (frequency counting)\n",
        "      * **Enjambment**: Line-ending punctuation rule\n",
        "      * **Simile**: Keyword patterns (“like”, “as…as”, “as if”)\n",
        "      * **Metaphor**: lwachowiak/Metaphor-Detection-XLMR\n",
        "\n",
        "      Although this doesn't a comprise an exhaustive list, it is aimed to exemplify at least the elegiac *tendencies* that the collected poems might have.\n",
        "\n",
        "      The analysis, being a comparative one, prioritizes rhetorical devices that are *computationally detectable*, ensuring that close and distant reading are methodologically balanced. Devices such as above leave identifiable linguistic patterns that can be captured through NLP tools which gives the distant reading analysis a fair fighting chance against the interpretative advantages of close reading.\n",
        "---\n",
        "*Note: The dataset was loaded onto the workbook as a CSV file where each entry had information in columns named Poem ID, Title, and Text.*"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "nHab60QhUI2_"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "### **1. Sentiment Analysis**\n",
        "The analysis employed the **[VADER](https://pypi.org/project/vaderSentiment/)** (Valence Aware Dictionary and sEntiment Reasoner) sentiment model, implemented through the **SentimentIntensityAnalyzer** module available in **[NLTK](https://www.nltk.org/)**. This object provides access to the VADER lexicon and scoring rules, enabling the computation of sentiment scores for each textual input."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "9A18ZQGJcTIw"
      }
    },
