              "summary": "{\n  \"name\": \"df\",\n  \"rows\": 10,\n  \"fields\": [\n    {\n      \"column\": \"Poem ID\",\n      \"properties\": {\n        \"dtype\": \"string\",\n        \"num_unique_values\": 10,\n        \"samples\": [\n          \"L38\",\n          \"A17\",\n          \"L03\"\n        ],\n        \"semantic_type\": \"\",\n        \"description\": \"\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"column\": \"compound\",\n      \"properties\": {\n        \"dtype\": \"number\",\n        \"std\": 0.011406840053231216,\n        \"min\": 0.9705,\n        \"max\": 0.9986,\n        \"num_unique_values\": 10,\n        \"samples\": [\n          0.9714,\n          0.998,\n          0.9779\n        ],\n        \"semantic_type\": \"\",\n        \"description\": \"\"\n      }\n    },\n    {\n      \"column\": \"Text\",\n      \"properties\": {\n        \"dtype\": \"string\",\n        \"num_unique_values\": 10,\n        \"samples\": [\n          \"for Benjamin Dodds\\n\\n\\u201cThe more time passes,\\nthe more I\\u2019m sorry about it.\\u201d\\n                                     \\u2014Oleg Garenko, Sputnik-2 scientist\\nLean and fast\\non all fours,\\nyour years of freezing\\nMoscow street smarts\\ncouldn\\u2019t save you\\nfrom the sweeping nets\\nof those KGB goons. Still,\\nit must have seemed great,\\nthree square meals,\\ntwo sisters for company,\\nand all that attention\\nfrom nice men in white,\\nuntil, each day, your cage\\ngrew steadily smaller,\\nthose dark noisy rides\\nwent faster and faster,\\nand your food turned to paste\\nfrom nondescript tubes,\\nwhen at last\\nthey shipped you out\\nto the Baikonur steppes,\\nyour body wired up\\nin your own special room,\\nwhere they oiled your fur\\nthen kissed your nose\\nand closed the door\\n                                                which\\nis when we burst in! Time\\ntravelling fantasists from\\nthe eventual future, armed\\nto the teeth with the\\nlatest gear and a\\nshaky plan. Sneaking in\\nafter nightfall, when the guards\\nare too drunk\\nand the scientists aren\\u2019t\\nparty members so they\\nwont stop us. I keep watch\\nwhile Ben cuts you free\\nand we make it downstairs\\nuntil Ben takes a round\\nin the back, poor bastard,\\nfrom the cowardly\\nbase commander that\\nI easily despatch with\\ntwenty-first century whispers\\nand make for gates\\nwhen at last Kalashnikovs\\nlight up the night\\nand the fresh heavy snow\\nbreaks my fall, turning\\npink all around me. Good\\ngirl I murmur good girl\\nas you tear toward\\nthe tree line and they\\ncall out after you\\nKudryavka\\n\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0               Zhuchka\\n\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0\\u00a0                           Limonchik\\nall the names that\\nwould never stick,\\nwhile Soviet 7.62\\ncracks Kahzak wood\\nand I watch you disappear\\ninto the safety of\\ndark forest, feeling it\\u2019s just\\nabout worth it, to know you\\u2019re free\\nto run through tall grass,\\neven if the world\\nwill never know your true name.\",\n          \"I knew my time was coming soon. \\nMy light, my ever-present light shone in the pitch inky blackness of life. From the moment I was born the only illumination I received was from that tiny bulb atop my head. A light used as a beacon of death for unsuspecting creatures, seeking shelter in the warmth of a light they\\u2019ve never been able to bask in before. I never asked for it to be the way that it is, but eat I must. My light was my livelihood, and was the calling of demise for others. \\nOnce shining bright, my light began to dull. It began to flicker. \\nI knew my time was coming soon.\\nMy body. Once strong and quick, had slowed. My fins struggled to move, my heart pounded harder with every inch I moved forward. It hurt to swim so much. It hurt to run from predators wanting to swallow me whole. It hurt to propel myself through the abyss that I had been born into. An abyss I was forced to stay in.\\nI knew my time was coming soon.\\nSomeone had told me once of a light so bright it lit up the entire planet in warmth. Miles and miles above us lie an entire world covered in brilliant light. Illuminated so wonderfully and beautifully that colors danced and swayed everywhere you looked. They told me of the light being a beacon of hope. A sign that time had passed and the darkness had ended for another day.\\nDown here, darkness was the only constant. \\nA light made for beauty? A light that everyone saw as a sign of joy? The only light I ever knew was the one I created myself. The light of death.\\nHow is it that another light could exist so amazingly? \\nI yearned to see it. \\nI yearned to feel its warmth. \\nYet, I was too far away. So far, the light didn\\u2019t dare penetrate our dismal domain. \\nSo I continued along, swimming. Eating. Killing. \\nBut my body is so tired.\\nMy use on this planet has been taken.\\nPerhaps I should just stop swimming.\\nI knew my time was coming soon.\\nAnd yet, I still thought of that light. That lifeline of light. \\nI wanted to see it. To gaze upon it. \\nWithout another thought, I found myself swimming.\\nJust like I always had.\\nBut this time, I was swimming up\\nUp.\\nUp.\\nUp.\\nFaster and faster I swam, my body straining as I pushed myself further.\\nBefore I knew it, I was far away from my inky depths. \\nI was somewhere a little warmer. \\nMy body began to feel like it was being stretched and compressed. \\nI felt like I was melting. It was hard to breathe.\\nBut I kept going. \\nUp.\\nUp. \\nFurther. \\nKeep going.\\nThe water was blue. Blue! A vast expanse of brilliance. Life began to spring itself towards me. Greens and pinks swaying. Absorbing.\\nWhat is this beauty?\\nI kept going. I had to keep going.\\nWas this what light could do?\\nCould my light have done this too?\\nI felt my lungs being crushed, my soul growing distant.\\nBut I held on. I held onto the hope of reaching the light.\\nThe water was swaying, pushing and pulling. \\nIt wasn\\u2019t still anymore.\\nIt was alive. The water was alive! \\nI pushed and pushed, I was so close I could taste it.\\nThe light.\\nThe glorious light.\\nAs I took my last breaths my body penetrated the crashing surface of the water. \\nAnd there it was.\\nThe light. \\nThe beautiful ball in the sky, shining so brightly. \\nIt was mighty, like a warrior. Its rays were warm on my cold, dying skin. \\nAs my vision blurred, I felt it.\\nI felt alive.\\nI had finally reached it.\\nMy last thought,\\ndistant and echoing.\\nWas that if I were to be reborn,\\nMaybe I could be a ball of light.\\nJust like this one.\\nAnd create a light for life.\\nAnd as I took my last breath I was so thankful.\\nSo very thankful.\\nFor the light I didn\\u2019t make.\",\n          \"Come now, little space dog,\\nOh Laika, what a brave space dog you are,\\nYou may not be with us now;\\nBut when we look up at the sky,\\nMay we remember your soul;\\nYou run around on Jupiter's moons,\\nLike the streets of Moscow on cold winter nights,\\nYou chase comets,\\nAs if they were little doves,\\nYou bite down satellites,\\nYou dance with stars,\\nThe entirety of Space is your play-place;\\nWhen scientists use their telescopes,\\nThey will surely go,\\n\\\"My, look at her go! The whole abyss is her's to play with!\\\",\\nWhen astronauts go to the moon,\\nI hope they will cherish you with belly rubs,\\nWe feel remorse for you;\\nThough, it seems you've become fond of your large field;\\nOh, Laika,\\nMay your story be told; and may you be cherished by the children as the space dog,\\nThe stray dogs of Moscow cherish your story,\\nNo one has forgotten you, little space dog,\\nAnd they never will. \"\n        ],\n        \"semantic_type\": \"\",\n        \"description\": \"\"\n      }\n    }\n  ]\n}"
