    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "***Function for finding Stress Patterns***\n",
        "\n",
        "The function takes a word as input and retrieves its phonetic transcription from the dictionary. In the CMU pronunciation format, vowel phonemes are marked with numerical stress indicators:\n",
        "\n",
        "* 0 = unstressed syllable\n",
        "* 1 = primary stress\n",
        "* 2 = secondary stress\n",
        "\n",
        "The stress markers are simplified into a binary stress representation since primary or secondary, a stress will be only that: phonemes marked with 0 are recorded as unstressed (U), while phonemes marked with 1 or 2 are recorded as stressed (S). The resulting sequence of U and S values forms the stress pattern for the word.\n",
        "\n",
        ">*Note: If a word is not present in the dictionary, the fallback value is an unstressed syllable. While this ensures the analysis can proceed without errors, it also represents a limitation, as unknown or unconventional words may be assigned an approximate stress pattern.*\n"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "iFbE0n8ko0Jz"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "def cmu_stress(word):\n",
        "\n",
        "    word = word.lower() # Lowercasing to match dictionary format\n",
        "\n",
        "    if word not in d:\n",
        "        return [\"U\"] # Fallback in case of unknown word (but of course, a limiation in its own right)\n",
        "\n",
        "    pron = d[word][0]\n",
        "\n",
        "    stress_pattern = []\n",
        "\n",
        "    for phoneme in pron:\n",
        "        if phoneme[-1].isdigit():\n",
        "\n",
        "            if phoneme[-1] == \"0\":\n",
        "                stress_pattern.append(\"U\")\n",
        "\n",
        "            else:\n",
        "                stress_pattern.append(\"S\")\n",
        "\n",
        "    return stress_pattern"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "0Zh9q4RsojNO"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "***Function for line-level Stress Pattern***\n",
        "\n",
        "The `cmu_stress()` function extended to consider whole lines using the [**RegEX**](https://docs.python.org/3/library/re.html) lookups.\n",
        ">*Note: This kind of RegEx matching is a strategy used throughout the analysis at various stages.*"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "jNnak8MTpMAY"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "import re\n",
        "\n",
        "def line_stress(line):\n",
        "\n",
        "    line = re.sub(r\"[^a-zA-Z\\s']\", \"\", line)\n",
        "\n",
        "    words = line.split()\n",
        "\n",
        "    pattern = []\n",
        "\n",
        "    for w in words:\n",
        "        pattern.extend(cmu_stress(w))\n",
        "\n",
        "    return pattern"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "ArU98fDBopY-"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "***[Regular Feet](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metrical_foot)***\n",
        "\n",
        "In poetry some feet are more regular than others including the **iamb**, **trochee**, **dactyl**, **anapest**, **spondee**, and **pyrrhus**."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "58S7mFPxroHz"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "FEET = {\n",
        "    # Disyllables\n",
        "    \"pyrrhus\": [\"U\",\"U\"],\n",
        "    \"iamb\": [\"U\",\"S\"],\n",
        "    \"trochee\": [\"S\",\"U\"],\n",
        "    \"spondee\": [\"S\",\"S\"],\n",
        "    \"dactyl\": [\"S\",\"U\",\"U\"],\n",
        "    \"amphibrach\": [\"U\",\"S\",\"U\"],\n",
        "    \"anapest\": [\"U\",\"U\",\"S\"]\n",
        "}"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "sE-W7HUiqGIk"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "***Function to Detect Foot***\n",
        "\n",
        "This step identified the dominant poetic foot within a line based on its stress pattern. The function scans the line’s stress sequence and compares it to the predefined foot templates above. It iterates across the sequence and counts how many times each foot pattern occurs, recording the counts using a frequency counter. The foot with the highest frequency is highlighted as the dominant foot for that line. If no clear match is detected, the function classifies the line as **irregular**.\n",
        "\n",
        ">*Note: This function relies on [collections](https://docs.python.org/3/library/collections.html#collections.Counter)' Counter subclass which counts  hashable items, i.e., items that can be used as a key in a Python dictionary, like words in a text or elements in a list, returning a dictionary-like object with the item counts. This is a tool that is implemented heavily throughout the analysis.*"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "uyVZcpJXs8-7"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "from collections import Counter\n",
        "\n",
        "def detect_foot(pattern):\n",
        "\n",
        "    counts = Counter()\n",
        "\n",
        "    for name, foot in FEET.items():\n",
        "\n",
        "        size = len(foot)\n",
        "\n",
        "        for i in range(0, len(pattern)-size+1):\n",
        "            if pattern[i:i+size] == foot:\n",
        "                counts[name]+=1\n",
        "\n",
        "    if counts:\n",
        "        return counts.most_common(1)[0][0]\n",
        "\n",
        "    return \"irregular\""
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "jvU64ZH0ri8K"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "***Function to Detect Meter***\n",
        "\n",
        "This function calculates the number of feet by dividing the total number of syllables by the typical syllable length of that foot identified using the above function (2 for iambs, 3 for anapests, etc.)."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "5Stf8G04tJXR"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "def detect_metre(pattern):\n",
        "\n",
        "    foot = detect_foot(pattern)\n",
        "    syllables = len(pattern)\n",
        "\n",
        "    if foot in [\"iamb\", \"trochee\", \"spondee\", \"pyrrhus\"]:\n",
        "        meter = syllables / 2\n",
        "    elif foot in [\"anapest\", \"dactyl\", \"amphibrach\"]:\n",
        "        meter = syllables / 3\n",
        "    else:\n",
        "        meter = None\n",
        "\n",
        "    return foot, meter"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "nsy_DpBTskhN"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "***Applying the functions on the dataset***\n",
        "\n",
        ">*Note: Each poem is split into individual lines, and empty lines are ignored.  The results—including poem ID, line text, syllable count, foot type, and number of feet—are stored in a list for further analysis.*"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "8BjY1WEcttDt"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "results = []\n",
        "\n",
        "for i,row in df.iterrows():\n",
        "\n",
        "    poem = row[\"Text\"]\n",
        "\n",
        "    lines = poem.split(\"\\n\")\n",
        "\n",
        "    for line in lines:\n",
        "\n",
        "        if line.strip()==\"\":\n",
        "            continue\n",
        "\n",
        "        pattern = line_stress(line)\n",
        "\n",
        "        foot, meter = detect_metre(pattern)\n",
        "\n",
        "        results.append({\n",
        "            \"poem\":row[\"Poem ID\"],\n",
        "            \"line\":line,\n",
        "            \"syllables\":len(pattern),\n",
        "            \"foot\":foot,\n",
        "            \"meter\":meter\n",
        "        })"
      ],
