    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "### **4. Rhetorical Devices**"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "auUvf7VFhRql"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "This section will try to study instances of **apostrophe, refrain, enjambment, metaphor, simile, and imagery** in the poems through various means and ends.\n",
        "\n",
        ">*Note: Here too, certain steps have been omitted for redundancy.*"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Av77QODDHqLY"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "***Apostrophe***\n",
        "\n",
        "This device enables \"*[a]n address to a dead or absent person, or personification as if he or she were present.*\" (Poetry Foundation) Eg: Walt Whitman's \"O Captain! My Captain!\"\n",
        "\n",
        "To this extent, this step will also consider the **speaker perspectives** in the poems at large to find patterns in that. The resultant second person narrators will point towards occurrences of apostrophe."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "DIqZbxARJS6F"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        ">*Reading the CSV*\n",
        ">\n",
        ">*Note: Sometimes the CSV must be re-read as df again to override the changes made to the df in the previous steps. A problem usually faced when working over multiple runtime sessions.*"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "m6iFA5KVMbQG"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "df = pd.read_csv(\"/content/Poems Metadata - Texts-2.csv\")"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "FqjiCm2eJ-4t"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        ">*Pronoun Dictionary*\n",
        ">\n",
        ">*Archaic versions like \"thee,\" \"thou\" are omitted since the corpus is wholly modern social media poetry.*"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "UhvSbpuoIHXU"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "first_person = {\"i\", \"me\", \"my\", \"mine\", \"we\", \"us\", \"our\", \"ours\"}\n",
        "second_person = {\"you\", \"your\", \"yours\"}\n",
        "third_person = {\"he\", \"him\", \"his\", \"she\", \"her\", \"hers\", \"they\", \"them\", \"their\", \"theirs\"}"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "C1nZ0YfCM2YI"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        ">*Function to Find Perspective*\n",
        ">\n",
        ">*This function counts the pronoun instances that match the dictionary defined above and computes the saturation of each pronoun type relative to the total, and ultimately picks the dominant one (one with highest proportion).*"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "5h3txHpqNg5Z"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "def detect_speaker(text):\n",
        "    if not isinstance(text, str) or text.strip() == \"\":\n",
        "        return \"Unknown\"\n",
        "\n",
        "    words = re.findall(r\"\\b\\w+\\b\", text.lower()) # Tokenisation and lowercases\n",
        "    counts = Counter(words)\n",
        "\n",
        "    # Pronoun counting\n",
        "    first_count = sum(counts[w] for w in first_person)\n",
        "    second_count = sum(counts[w] for w in second_person)\n",
        "    third_count = sum(counts[w] for w in third_person)\n",
        "\n",
        "    total = first_count + second_count + third_count\n",
        "    if total == 0:\n",
        "        return \"Unknown\"\n",
        "\n",
        "    # Saturation in poem\n",
        "    saturation = {\n",
        "        \"First-Person\": first_count / total,\n",
        "        \"Second-Person\": second_count / total,\n",
        "        \"Third-Person\": third_count / total\n",
        "    }\n",
        "\n",
        "    speaker = max(saturation, key=saturation.get) # Speaker = perspective with highest proportion\n",
        "\n",
        "    return speaker"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "3GJq9s_mNnse"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        ">*Applying the function*"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "YYiAyFQPOE_0"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "df['Speaker'] = df['Text'].apply(detect_speaker) # Results stored in new column \"Speaker\"\n",
        "df.head()"
      ],
