    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        "***Simile***\n",
        "\n",
        "A simile is figurative device that explicitly establishes likeness between two different things using words like “as,” “like,” or “than.” (Poetry Foundation) These are found in all sorts of poems, including Lord Tennyson's \"In Memoriam\" Canto 5."
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "aUZN_eP52jdS"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        ">*Defining Simile Pattern*\n",
        ">\n",
        ">*The pattern list isn't exhaustive, since similes can appear in many forms that rule-based detection may not capture, but should function well as a heuristic indicator, given its basis in most typical comparative structures in English.*"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "eeWeEEvB6L5p"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "patterns = [\n",
        "    r\"\\blike a\\b\",\n",
        "    r\"\\blike an\\b\",\n",
        "    r\"\\blike the\\b\",\n",
        "    r\"\\bas(?:\\s+\\w+){1,5}\\s+as\\b\", # Allows up to 5 words between as...as\n",
        "    r\"\\bas if\\b\",\n",
        "    r\"\\bas though\\b\",\n",
        "    r\"\\bmore(?:\\s+\\w+){1,5}\\s+than\\b\",  # Allows up to 5 words between more...than\n",
        "    r\"\\bless(?:\\s+\\w+){1,5}\\s+than\\b\"  # Allows up to 5 words between less...than\n",
        "]"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "SiFhsZE01kwm"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        ">*Function to Detect Simile*\n",
        ">\n",
        ">*This function will split each poem into lines and check each line against the defined simile patterns and count those lines containing such occurrences.*"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "6fKp8HD270eO"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "def detect_similes(text):\n",
        "\n",
        "    lines = text.lower().split(\"\\n\") # The text is lowercased and split into lines by pre-processing convention\n",
        "\n",
        "    simile_count = 0\n",
        "\n",
        "    for line in lines:\n",
        "        if any(re.search(p, line) for p in patterns):\n",
        "            simile_count += 1\n",
        "\n",
        "    return pd.Series([simile_count, len(lines)])"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "8nj86On573DU"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        ">*Applying Function*\n",
        ">\n",
        ">*This function also finds the how many lines in a poem contain similes (`simile_count`) and the total lines in the poem (`len(lines)`).*"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "Kms8Tz-l78ea"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
        "df[['Simile_Count', 'Total_Lines']] = df['Text'].apply(detect_similes)"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "xfkBdnRq78M4"
      },
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "source": [
        ">*Categorising according to Subject*\n",
        ">\n",
        ">*The proportion of simile presence is calculated as ratio and then categorised for easier appraisal.*"
      ],
      "metadata": {
        "id": "cJRKWtL68EyR"
      }
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "source": [
